      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">CVR</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Conversion rate</strong> is the percentage of users who take a specific desired action out of the total number of visitors. The formula is <strong>(Conversions ÷ Total Visitors) × 100</strong>. The average website converts at 2-3%; the top 25% of landing pages convert above 5.31%. Doubling this number has the same revenue effect as doubling traffic — usually faster and cheaper.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Average landing page</div>
            <div class="tms-value">2.35%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">CRO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Top 25% pages</div>
            <div class="tms-value">5.31%+</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Traffic without conversion is a bill. Conversion without traffic is a rounding error. Every serious growth team measures both — but the leverage sits in conversion, because it is the multiplier on every future dollar of ad spend.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is conversion rate?</h2>
        <p>Conversion rate measures how efficiently a page, campaign, or funnel turns visitors into completed actions. What counts as a "conversion" depends on the business:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ecommerce</strong> — completed purchase</li>
          <li><strong>SaaS</strong> — trial signup or paid activation</li>
          <li><strong>Local service</strong> — phone call or booking form</li>
          <li><strong>Publisher</strong> — email newsletter subscription</li>
          <li><strong>B2B</strong> — demo request or gated content download</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The formula stays constant regardless of the goal: divide conversions by visitors, multiply by 100. Every page can have its own rate — homepage, product page, pricing page — and comparing per-page rates is more useful than a site-wide average.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Where the benchmarks come from</div>
          <p>Unbounce's 2024 landing-page report found the median conversion rate across 33,000 pages was <strong>2.35%</strong>, the top quartile hit <strong>5.31%</strong>, and the top 10% exceeded <strong>11.45%</strong>. Google Ads search-network average sits at <strong>3.75%</strong> (WordStream). These are the numbers to beat.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why conversion rate matters</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Revenue multiplier.</strong> Doubling conversion rate has the same effect as doubling traffic — but does not require doubling the ad budget.</li>
          <li><strong>Paid-media efficiency.</strong> A 5% converter can outbid a 1.5% converter on the same keyword because every click is worth 3.3x more.</li>
          <li><strong>Product-market-fit signal.</strong> Declining conversion rate on stable traffic almost always means the promise-to-delivery gap widened.</li>
          <li><strong>CAC control.</strong> Higher conversion rate lowers <a href="/glossary/customer-acquisition-cost/">customer acquisition cost</a> without changing anything upstream.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to calculate conversion rate</h2>
        <p>The formula is one line. What matters is defining the numerator and denominator precisely.</p>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># The formula</span><br>
          Conversion Rate = (Conversions <span class="uf-arrow">÷</span> Total Visitors) <span class="uf-arrow">×</span> 100<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Example — SaaS landing page</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Visitors:</span> 4,200<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Trial signups:</span> 168<br>
          <span class="uf-status">Conversion rate = 4.00%</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Macro vs micro conversions</h3>
        <p>A <strong>macro conversion</strong> is the primary business goal — a sale or paid signup. A <strong>micro conversion</strong> is an intermediate step — a video view, pricing page visit, or add-to-cart. Track both. Macro rates drive revenue; micro rates diagnose where macro rates go wrong.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of conversion rate</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>What it measures</th><th>2026 benchmark</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Website CVR</strong></td><td>All conversions ÷ site visitors</td><td>2-3%</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Landing page CVR</strong></td><td>Conversions on a single page</td><td>2.35% median</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Ecommerce CVR</strong></td><td>Purchases ÷ product visitors</td><td>1.5-3%</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Email CVR</strong></td><td>Actions ÷ email clicks</td><td>4-10%</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Paid ad CVR</strong></td><td>Conversions ÷ ad clicks</td><td>3.75% (search)</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real conversion rate examples</h2>
        <h3>1. HVAC company — added click-to-call</h3>
        <p>An HVAC company was converting the contact form at <strong>1.5%</strong> — 45 leads a month from 3,000 visitors. Adding a persistent phone-number header (click-to-call on mobile) doubled that to <strong>3%</strong> — 90 leads a month. Same traffic, same offer, one UX change.</p>

        <h3>2. DTC skincare — simplified checkout</h3>
        <p>A skincare brand moved from a 4-step checkout to a 2-step. Mobile conversion jumped from <strong>1.2% to 2.1%</strong> — a 75% relative lift on the biggest revenue-driver in the funnel.</p>

        <h3>3. SaaS trial — dedicated landing page</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company was sending Facebook ads to their homepage and converting at <strong>2%</strong>. A dedicated landing page matching the ad copy pushed the same traffic to <strong>5%</strong> — a 2.5x lift with zero change in ad spend.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Conversion rate vs CTR — which is which</h2>
        <p>Both are percentages. They measure completely different stages.</p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Conversion rate</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Measured on the destination page</li>
              <li>Numerator = completed actions</li>
              <li>Reflects offer + UX + fit</li>
              <li>Owned by CRO and product</li>
              <li>Example: 4% of visitors bought</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4><a href="/glossary/click-through-rate/">Click-through rate (CTR)</a></h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Measured on the referring surface</li>
              <li>Numerator = clicks</li>
              <li>Reflects headline + creative + audience</li>
              <li>Owned by paid media and SEO</li>
              <li>Example: 6% of ad viewers clicked</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>High CTR with low conversion rate almost always means the ad or headline promised something the page did not deliver. Fix the mismatch.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 ways to lift conversion rate</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Fix page speed first.</strong> A 1-second delay drops conversions by <strong>7%</strong> (Portent, 2019). Compress images, defer JavaScript, use a CDN.</li>
          <li><strong>Match the ad promise on the page.</strong> The scent of the click must continue on arrival.</li>
          <li><strong>One page, one goal.</strong> Multiple CTAs split attention. Landing pages should have one primary action.</li>
          <li><strong>Cut form fields.</strong> Every extra field drops conversion by 4-8%. Ask only for what sales genuinely need.</li>
          <li><strong>Show social proof above the fold.</strong> Reviews, logos, customer counts. Personalized CTAs alone convert 202% better than generic ones (HubSpot).</li>
          <li><strong>Test headlines first.</strong> Highest-leverage A/B test on any landing page.</li>
          <li><strong>Segment by traffic source.</strong> Do not optimise an average — optimise the source that matters.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — celebrating conversion lift without checking revenue</div>
          <p>Conversion rate can rise while revenue falls if the winning variant shifts users to a cheaper product. Always tie CVR to revenue-per-visitor. A 20% conversion lift on a $9 plan can lose to a 10% lift on a $99 plan.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common conversion rate mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Measuring only the sitewide average.</strong> Hides per-page and per-source truth.</li>
          <li><strong>Stopping A/B tests early.</strong> Tests need at least 100 conversions per variation for reliable results.</li>
          <li><strong>Testing tiny changes.</strong> Button-color tweaks rarely move the needle. Test headlines, offers, and layouts.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring qualitative data.</strong> Analytics tell what; session recordings tell why.</li>
          <li><strong>Comparing to industry averages instead of history.</strong> Your own trend line matters more than a WordStream table.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What is a good conversion rate?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>The average website conversion rate is 2-3%. Top-performing landing pages achieve 5-10%, and the top quartile hits 5.31% or higher. Benchmarks vary by industry — ecommerce averages 1.5-3%, Google Ads search averages 3.75%.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How is conversion rate calculated?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Divide conversions by total visitors and multiply by 100. Example: 30 signups from 1,000 visitors is (30 / 1,000) x 100 = 3% conversion rate. Always define what a conversion is before you measure.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Why is my conversion rate low?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>The five biggest killers are slow page speed, unclear value proposition, excessive form fields, mismatched audience targeting, and a weak call-to-action. A 1-second load delay alone reduces conversions by 7%.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Does more traffic lower conversion rate?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Not automatically — it depends on traffic quality. Broad untargeted campaigns dilute conversion rate. Well-matched intent-based traffic can lift it. Segment conversion rate by traffic source to see the truth.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between conversion rate and CTR?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Click-through rate (CTR) measures clicks from a search result, email, or ad. Conversion rate measures completed actions after arrival. High CTR with low conversion means the ad or headline overpromised what the landing page delivers.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

